    "E9": "**Recommendation: Option A — Capability-thresholds licensing.**\n\nThe coalition should adopt capability-threshold licensing as its primary frontier AI governance framework, with thresholds defined in measurable terms—training compute, model capability evaluations, and deployment-risk triggers—and reviewed every 12 months. My confidence is moderate, roughly 65%, but this has the highest expected value given the coalition’s objectives and the 18-month implementation window. The key reason is enforceability.",
    "E10": "**Recommendation: Option C — Rights-and-process-based governance.**\n\nThis framework is the only candidate that begins with the humanist question: who is affected, and how? By codifying transparency, contestability, explanation, and opt-out, it places dignity and agency at the center of the digital economy. Vulnerable parties—welfare applicants screened by opaque algorithms, gig workers managed by automated systems, migrants facing biased translation tools—gain enforceable standing to challenge harms before they compound."
